### Software
[Brackets](http://brackets.io) - Over the past year I've switched between four code editors on my Windows machine. Brackets is by far my favorite because of its simple user-interface and number of extensions. [Adobe Edge Code]() is fork of Brackets maintained by Adobe. 

[Notepad++](http://notepad-plus-plus.org/) (Windows) - A classic editor I use when I need to make a quick edit. The UI and highlighting isn't as nice on the eye as other editors, but it works in pinch. 

[Coda 2](http://panic.com/coda/) - (Mac OSX, $30) - While Coda 2 is somewhat expensive considering your free options it was really worth it. It is more of a powerhorse then any other code editor I use. Think of Dreamweaver, but for the modern web designer. It has built in shell, FTP, and Git. I really like using it when working on my MacBook Pro.

I use the [Git App](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.romanenco.gitt&hl=en) (Android) and [Github for Windows](http://windows.github.com/) &amp; [Github for Mac](http://mac.github.com/) for version control. I have also used [SourceTree](http://www.sourcetreeapp.com/) (Mac OSX/Windows) for Git repositories not on Github, but I definitely perfer the Github GUI over any other application. It is simple and gets the job done. I also have a [Zenhub.io](https://www.zenhub.io/) acount, which is a nice app for Github that you can use to make managing issues better. Think Trello boards + Github issues = Zenhub.

[CodeAnywhere](https://codeanywhere.net/) (iOS/Android) is a nice app for editing files on your phone via FTP.
[S3 Browser](http://s3browser.com/) is an application for uploading files to Amazon S3; I it like because of the HTTP header settings.

